r hop varieties. We are a test brewery – our Innovations Brewery is a state-of-the-art facility where you can experiment with new recipes, techniques and varieties. We are an resource – home to the Hops Academy where brewers can get a better understanding of the complexity of hops. We are partners – fellow beer lovers who understand why you need flexible and creative contracts. But most of all, we are an innovators – tireless professionals who are passionate about providing you with the products, tools, services and supply assurance you need to brew great beer. And isn’t that why you’re here?'),(1790,259,'_about-overview_0_about-overview-text','field_548f0bef607ed'),(1791,259,'about-overview_0_about-overview-image','65'),(1792,259,'_about-overview_0_about-overview-image','field_548f0c1b607ee'),(1793,259,'about-overview','1'),(1794,259,'_about-overview','field_548f08cf607ea'),(1795,259,'about-history_0_about-history-header','THE BACKSTORY'),(1796,259,'_about-history_0_about-history-header','field_548f0e20607f0'),(1797,259,'about-history_0_about-history-subheader',''),(1798,259,'_about-history_0_about-history-subheader','field_548f139907dda'),(1799,259,'about-history_0_about-history-left','Like many of our innovative hop varieties, the history of Haas is a cross-pollination – the careful combination of people, agronomy, technology and innovation that has resulted in a company that is constantly evolving to meet the needs of our customers.\r\n\r\nIt all started in 1914 when young man from Britain, born to Austrian-American parents, found himself waiting tables in Nuremberg, Germany. His name was John I Haas. One of his regular patrons was a mid-sized hop trader by the name of Mr. Bing who saw a spark in John (or John I, as his friends called him) and tried to recruit him into joining his hop business. Instead, John I decided to start his own hop business — in America.'),(1800,259,'_about-history_0_about-history-left','field_548f0e74607f3'),(1801,259,'about-history_0_about-history-right','<a href=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/blackberry.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-64\" src=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/blackberry.jpg\" alt=\"blackberry\" width=\"377\" height=\"290\" /></a>'),(1802,259,'_about-history_0_about-history-right','field_548f0e87607f4'),(1803,259,'about-history_1_about-history-header','PROHIBITION AND BEYOND'),(1804,259,'_about-history_1_about-history-header','field_548f0e20607f0'),(1805,259,'about-history_1_about-history-subheader',''),(1806,259,'_about-history_1_about-history-subheader','field_548f139907dda'),(1807,259,'about-history_1_about-history-left','Despite a rocky start, which included both World War I and, of course, Prohibition, his hop business grew because of his initiative to look for customers outside the United States. In particular, Haas built strong relationships with Canadian brewers who, not surprisingly, were benefiting greatly from American Prohibition. In 1925, John I acquired his first hop farm in the Fraser Valley of British Columbia (which eventually grew to 1,300 acres).\r\n\r\nThen in 1931, Haas sensed a change in what the world’s brewers were looking for. He bought a bought a farm in Yakima, Washington and instead of growing Clusters and Fuggles hops (which were seeded and of bad picking quality),'),(1808,259,'_about-history_1_about-history-left','field_548f0e74607f3'),(1809,259,'about-history_1_about-history-right','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/prohibition-beyond2.jpg\"> he implemented a program to reduce the seed content and improve the picking quality of his hops. He named the hop, and his farm, Yakima Golding and the brewers responded in droves. This innovation, the first of many, led to rapid growth and Haas became the world’s largest private hop grower in the world with 25 farms and almost 4,000 acres.</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/prohibition-beyond2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-68\" src=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/prohibition-beyond.jpg\" alt=\"prohibition-beyond\" width=\"293\" height=\"149\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/prohibition-beyond2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-62\" src=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/prohibition-beyond2.jpg\" alt=\"prohibition-beyond2\" width=\"297\" height=\"141\" /></a>'),(1810,259,'_about-history_1_about-history-right','field_548f0e87607f4'),(1811,259,'about-history_2_about-history-header','HAAS AND BARTH. '),(1812,259,'_about-history_2_about-history-header','field_548f0e20607f0'),(1813,259,'about-history_2_about-history-subheader','FROM COMPETITORS TO COLLABORATORS'),(1814,259,'_about-history_2_about-history-subheader','field_548f139907dda'),(1815,259,'about-history_2_about-history-left','For the next 40 years, Haas maintained its leadership position in America but faced increasing pressure abroad from the Joh Barth &amp; Sons, a German hop company based in Nuremberg that began operations as far back as 1794. At times, the competition was fierce with each company used its expertise and innovation to try to get an edge on the other. But after Fred Haas took over for John I in 1964, the two companies realized they had more in common than the flower they grew – the drive for innovation, the obsession with quality and the core belief that while their fine hops got their customers to come, but it was service that got them to come back. So when the time came for Fred to step down as President, he approached _______ about buying his company. The result was that in 1978, John I Haas became part of the Barth-Haas Group – the world’s leading hops supplier.'),(1816,259,'_about-history_2_about-history-left','field_548f0e74607f3'),(1817,259,'about-history_2_about-history-right','<a href=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/haas-brath.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-63\" src=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/haas-brath.jpg\" alt=\"haas-brath\" width=\"296\" height=\"280\" /></a>'),(1818,259,'_about-history_2_about-history-right','field_548f0e87607f4'),(1819,259,'about-history_3_about-history-header','HAAS TODAY:\r\n100 YEARS YOUNG ONE'),(1820,259,'_about-history_3_about-history-header','field_548f0e20607f0'),(1821,259,'about-history_3_about-history-subheader',''),(1822,259,'_about-history_3_about-history-subheader','field_548f139907dda'),(1823,259,'about-history_3_about-history-left','In the years that followed, Haas maintained its passion for innovation. In the 1990’s, the Haas hop breeding program brought the hop varieties Chelan and Millennium into the world. More recently, Haas partnered with Select Botanicals LLC to create a joint venture called the Hop Breeding Company LLC which created the highly successful varieties Citra as Citra®, Mosaic® and Equinox™.\r\n\r\nToday, the John I Haas company continues to lead the way. In 2013, Haas opened the Innovations Brewery inside our recently opened Innovations Center in Yakima, Washington. This 2.5 hectoliter experimental brewery has the advanced capabilities that allow our'),(1824,259,'_about-history_3_about-history-left','field_548f0e74607f3'),(1825,259,'about-history_3_about-history-right','brewmasters to work with commercial brewers large and small to develop beer formulations that utilize new hop varieties, hop products and innovative flavor concepts.\r\n\r\nIn 2014, Haas celebrated its 100th anniversary. And while John I might have trouble recognizing some of today’s modern facilities, we are certain he would see the same obsession with innovation, quality and service that he set the standard for from the very beginning.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/abt-history-logo.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-67\" src=\"http://haas.shotgunflat8.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/abt-history-logo.png\" alt=\"abt-history-logo\" width=\"361\" height=\"112\" /></a>'),(1826,259,'_about-history_3_about-history-right','field_548f0e87607f4'),(1827,259,'about-history','4'),(1828,259,'_about-history','field_548f0c37607ef'),(1829,259,'about-facilities-fields_0_about-facilities-fields-header','GROWING, PICKING AND PROCESSING YOUR HOPS'),(1830,259,'_about-facilities-fields_0_about-facilities-fields-header','field_548f0ecf607f5'),(1831,259,'about-facilities-fields_0_about-facilities-fields-text','While the John I Haas company commissions many of the hops we sell from high-quality partner growers in the Yakima valley, we also grow, breed and process hops on our own Yakima Golding farm. This 1,400 acre facility was the original farm purchased by John I. Haas back in 1931 when he first came to the Yakima valley. It features trellised farmland for growing the hops as well as elaborate picking machines, hop kilns and baling operations.\r\n\r\nAll this is supported by highly qualified, innovative and experienced farm management personnel, supporting the production of the major U.S. hop varieties. Haas benefits from a dedicated and experienced seasonal workforce that is provided modern housing facilities for the time they are with us during the growing season and harvest.'),(1832,259,'_about-facilities-fields_0_about-facilities-fields-text','field_548f0ee6607f6'),(1833,259,'about-facilities-fields_0_about-facilities-fields-image','66'),(1834,259,'_about-facilities-fields_0_about-facilities-fields-image','field_548f0efd607f7'),(1835,259,'about-facilities-fields','1'),(1836,259,'_about-facilities-fields','field_548f0e35607f1'),(1837,259,'about-team','a:8:{i:0;s:3:\"205\";i:1;s:3:\"204\";i:2;s:3:\"216\";i:3;s:3:\"217\";i:4;s:3:\"218\";i:5;s:3:\"219\";i:6;s:3:\"220\";i:7;s:3:\"221\";}'),(1838,259,'_about-team','field_548f0e47607f2'),(1839,260,'about-overview_0_about-overview-header','HAAS. F