ttachment','image/jpeg',0),(1022,2,'2015-08-14 21:41:21','2015-08-14 21:41:21','Distinction is the aim for brewers these days, and the newer Australian hop varieties are providing it in a big way.  Oskar Blues, brewing in the USA out of Colorado and North Carolina, has released their “Oskar Blues IPA” showcasing a number of Aussie flavor hops developed from the Hop Products Australia (HPA) breeding program.  As part of the Barth-Haas Group, HPA has had great success in developing amazing hops and garnering world-wide attention.  The variety Galaxy™, has been a huge hit, but as Oskar Blues can attest to, other exciting up-and-comers are Enigma™, Vic Secret™, Ella™, and Topaz™ – all grown in the Australian hop-growing regions of Tasmania and Victoria.\r\n\r\nTo read the full story, click <a href=\"http://www.examiner.com/article/oskar-blues-brewery-releases-oskar-blues-ipa-as-newest-year-round-offering\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Oskar Blues Loves Australian Flavor Hops','As part of the Barth-Haas Group, Hop Products Australia (HPA) has had great success in developing amazing hops and garnering world-wide attention.  The variety “Galaxy” has been a huge hit, but as Oskar Blues can attest to, other exciting up-and-comers are Enigma, Vic Secret, Ella, and Topaz – all grown in the Australian hop-growing regions of Tasmania and Victoria.','publish','closed','closed','','oskar-blues-loves-australian-flavor-hops','','','2015-08-14 21:41:21','2015-08-14 21:41:21','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/?post_type=news-events&#038;p=1022',0,'news-events','',0),(1024,6,'2015-08-06 18:40:02','2015-08-06 18:40:02','','OskarBluesIPA','','inherit','open','open','','oskarbluesipa','','','2015-08-06 18:40:02','2015-08-06 18:40:02','',1022,'http://www.johnihaas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/OskarBluesIPA.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1026,6,'2015-08-06 18:43:32','2015-08-06 18:43:32','','OskarBluesIPA','','inherit','open','open','','oskarbluesipa-2','','','2015-08-06 18:43:32','2015-08-06 18:43:32','',1022,'http://www.johnihaas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/OskarBluesIPA1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1028,1,'2015-08-09 13:42:44','2015-08-09 13:42:44','','RockneyRoberts@Gmail.com submitted an inquiry on 08/9/2015','','publish','open','open','','rockneyrobertsgmail-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-0892015','','','2015-08-09 13:42:44','2015-08-09 13:42:44','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/contact/rockneyrobertsgmail-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-0892015/',0,'contact','',0),(1029,6,'2015-08-10 13:14:00','2015-08-10 13:14:00','Sales position for BetaTec Hop Products. Provide and develop technical sales services and marketing strategies for the bio-ethanol, baker’s yeast, spirits and beet sugar markets for hop based products. This position covers the upper Midwest of the United States, particularly the states of North and South Dakota, Kansas, Nebraska and Iowa.   Self –starter that can work from home and travel approximately 60% of time.   Requirements are a Bachelor of Science degree (preferably technical) and ten plus years of technical sales experience. (Bio-ethanol sales experience a plus.\r\n\r\n<a class=\"readmore-btn inquire-btn\" href=\"mailto:hr@johnihaas.com\">INQUIRE</a>','Technical Sales Manager, Ethanol, Sugar & Yeast Markets','','publish','closed','closed','','technical-sales-manager-ethanol-sugar-yeast-markets','','','2015-08-10 13:14:00','2015-08-10 13:14:00','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/?post_type=career&#038;p=1029',0,'career','',0),(1030,1,'2015-08-13 18:54:10','2015-08-13 18:54:10','','mike@brickerpublishing.com submitted an inquiry on 08/13/2015','','publish','open','open','','mikebrickerpublishing-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08132015','','','2015-08-13 18:54:10','2015-08-13 18:54:10','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/contact/mikebrickerpublishing-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08132015/',0,'contact','',0),(1032,1,'2015-08-14 14:51:23','2015-08-14 14:51:23','','bd2004@me.com submitted an inquiry on 08/14/2015','','publish','open','open','','bd2004me-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08142015','','','2015-08-14 14:51:23','2015-08-14 14:51:23','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/contact/bd2004me-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08142015/',0,'contact','',0),(1033,2,'2015-08-06 13:54:07','2015-08-06 13:54:07','<p class=\"deck\">Chris Cramer shares the story behind Mosaic Session Ale, now one of Karl Strauss Brewing Company’s most successful and popular beers. The beer’s development began in 2012, when the Hop Breeding Company—a consortium of hop farmers and John I. Haas up in Yakima—developed a new variety called HBC369. They wanted to share the new hop with a select group of brewers and wanted to see how the brewers would use it. Karl Strauss was one of the select few breweries that got to play with HBC369, but only with tiny little bits of it. “Our brewers were immediately intrigued by it,” Chris recalls. “It was so distinctly aromatic. It had such incredible grapefruit, tropical fruit, passion fruit, and peach aromas to it. It was citrusy and crisp, and it was an unusual hop in that you could use it for both aromatics and for bittering.” So, in 2013, the brewers at Karl Strauss gave the growers an order to send as much HBC369 as they could.</p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.sandiegomagazine.com/Blogs/Behind-the-Brews/Summer-2015/I-Married-a-Hop/\" target=\"_blank\">READ MORE</a>','\"I Married a Hop\"','Mosaic Session Ale began development in 2012, when the Hop Breeding Company—a consortium of hop farmers and John I. Haas up in Yakima—developed a new variety called HBC369.','publish','closed','closed','','i-married-a-hop','','','2015-09-03 13:55:08','2015-09-03 13:55:08','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/?post_type=news-events&#038;p=1033',0,'news-events','',0),(1034,6,'2015-08-14 17:49:05','2015-08-14 17:49:05','','karl-strauss-mosaic-session-ale-0afc89f5','','inherit','open','open','','karl-strauss-mosaic-session-ale-0afc89f5','','','2015-08-14 17:49:05','2015-08-14 17:49:05','',1033,'http://www.johnihaas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/karl-strauss-mosaic-session-ale-0afc89f5.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1035,13,'2015-08-21 17:14:10','2015-08-21 17:14:10','<a href=\"#English\">To read the English translation, click here.</a>\r\n<h3>BRASIL BRAU JULY 2015</h3>\r\nA semana da Brasil Brau foi sem dúvida cheia e muito proveitosa. Para o Grupo Barth- Haas ela começou na cidade de São Paulo com duas noites da Hops Academy (nossa Academia de Lúpulos) realizada no Instituto da Cerveja Brasil, onde um grupo de 20 pessoas – de cervejeiros caseiros a artesanais e até mesmo cervejeiros de duas grandes cervejerias – recebeu informações valiosas sobre esta planta preciosa, variedades, seleção de lúpulos, processamento, produtos e aplicações. Os três dias que se seguiram foram tomados por atividades relacionadas à Brasil Brau em si. E nossa semana finalmente terminou aproximadamente 900 km ao sul de onde começou, mais precisamente na linda cidade de Bento Gonçalves, na Serra Gaúcha, em uma reunião na sede da LNF Latino Americana, nossos distribuidores exclusivos para o setor de “Cervejas Artesanais” no Brasil, Uruguai e Paraguai.\r\n\r\nEm nossa estação de demonstração de nosso “Pure Hop Aroma” (PHA) os cervejeiros tiveram a chance para aprender sobre esta linha de produtos e suas vantagens em relação ao processo de dry-hopping no que se refere à redução de perdas de cerveja, facilidade de dosagem e sua flexibilidade no desenvolvimento de novas cervejas. Um fardo aberto de lúpulo Cascade em flor causou inesperado encanto quando cervejeiros simplismente tiveram a oportunidade de sentir o lúpulo com suas próprias mãos, colher amostras e fazer uma rápida avaliação sensorial do mesmo.\r\n\r\n<a name=\"English\"></a>\r\n\r\nConforme o mercado brasileiro de cervejas artesanais amadurece em ritmo acelerado, podemos certamente afirmar nossa presença no mesmo com um dos slogans exibidos em nosso estande, o qual dizia: “Loucos por lúpulos. Loucos para ajudá-los a desenvolver sua próxima grande cerveja.” Esta é a nossa missão… Do lúpulo para a torneira!\r\n\r\nSaúde!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>BRAZIL BRAU JULY 2015</h3>\r\nThe Brasil Brau week was undoubtedly full and fruitful. For the Barth-Haas Group it started out in São Paulo City with two evenings of our Hops Academy at the <em>Instituto da Cerveja Brasil</em>, where a group of 20+ people – from home through craft brewers and a few from two very large breweries – were given valuable information about our precious plant, varieties, hop selection, processing, products and applications. The following three days were filled with activities related to the trade show itself. And our week finally ended about 900 km south of where it started, more precisely in the beautiful city of Bento Gonçalves, RS, in a business meeting with our exclusive partner distributor <em>LNF Latino Americana</em> for the Craft Brewing sector in Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay.\r\n\r\nAt our <em>Pure Hop Aroma (PHA)</em> demonstration station, brewers really took their time to learn about the product line and its advantages related to dry-hopping when it comes to reduced beer losses, ease of application and flexibility for the development of new beers. An open bale of Cascade raw hop caused an unexpected delight when brewers could simply stick their hands in it, take samples and do some casual rub-and sniff activities.\r\n\r\nAs the Brazilian craft beer market matures at such an amazingly fast pace, we can certainly affirm our presence in it with one of the slogans displayed on our booth, which read in Brazilian Portuguese: <em>“Wild about hops. Dedicated to help you develop your next great-tasting beer!” </em>This is our goal… From Hop to Tap!\r\n\r\nProst!','Brasil Brau July 2015','The Brasil Brau week was undoubtedly full and fruitful. For the Barth-Haas Group it started out in São Paulo City with two evenings of our Hops Academy at the Instituto da Cerveja Brasil, where a group of 20+ people - from home through craft brewers and a few from two very large breweries - were given valuable information about our precious plant, varieties, hop selection, processing, products and applications. ','publish','open','open','','brasil-brau-july-2015','','','2015-09-09 17:15:30','2015-09-09 17:15:30','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/?post_type=blog&#038;p=1035',0,'blog','',0),(1036,6,'2015-08-14 18:06:27','2015-08-14 18:06:27','','Untitled','','inherit','open','open','','untitled','','','2015-08-14 18:06:27','2015-08-14 18:06:27','',1035,'http://www.johnihaas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Untitled.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1037,1,'2015-08-15 03:30:01','2015-08-15 03:30:01','','vince@svbrewing.com submitted an inquiry on 08/15/2015','','publish','open','open','','vincesvbrewing-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08152015','','','2015-08-15 03:30:01','2015-08-15 03:30:01','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/contact/vincesvbrewing-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08152015/',0,'contact','',0),(1039,1,'2015-08-17 12:40:50','2015-08-17 12:40:50','','Haas_one-pager','','inherit','open','open','','haas_one-pager','','','2015-08-17 12:40:50','2015-08-17 12:40:50','',851,'http://www.johnihaas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Haas_one-pager.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(1040,1,'2015-08-17 12:43:19','2015-08-17 12:43:19','','resource-library','','inherit','open','open','','resource-library','','','2015-08-17 12:43:19','2015-08-17 12:43:19','',851,'http://www.johnihaas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/resource-library.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1041,6,'2015-08-17 19:01:51','2015-08-17 19:01:51','We have an opening in our state-of-the-art research brewery for an Assistant Brewer. This is a “hands-on” technical brewing position with involvement in all aspects of the daily operation. Activities include laboratory analysis of beer/yeast, CIP of tanks/vessels, packaging beer for analysis, cleaning of brewery areas, management of raw materials and general assistance for the brewery operations. The successful candidate will bring to the position a strong knowledge of good laboratory practices, instrumentation/computer experience, fermentation knowledge and an insatiable passion for brewing beer. Salary DOE and excellent benefit package provided.\r\n\r\n<a class=\"readmore-btn inquire-btn\" href=\"mailto:hr@johnihaas.com\">INQUIRE</a>','Assistant Brewer','','publish','closed','closed','','assistant-brewer','','','2015-08-17 19:01:51','2015-08-17 19:01:51','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/?post_type=career&#038;p=1041',0,'career','',0),(1043,1,'2015-08-31 22:51:25','2015-08-31 22:51:25','','lis.findley@outlook.com submitted an inquiry on 08/31/2015','','publish','open','open','','lis-findleyoutlook-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08312015','','','2015-08-31 22:51:25','2015-08-31 22:51:25','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/contact/lis-findleyoutlook-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-08312015/',0,'contact','',0),(1044,1,'2015-09-01 22:16:03','2015-09-01 22:16:03','','eludiumpu36@yahoo.com submitted an inquiry on 09/1/2015','','publish','open','open','','eludiumpu36yahoo-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-0912015','','','2015-09-01 22:16:03','2015-09-01 22:16:03','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/contact/eludiumpu36yahoo-com-submitted-an-inquiry-on-0912015/',0,'contact','',0),(1045,8,'2015-09-11 13:40:17','2015-09-11 13:40:17','All across the U.S., September is many people’s favorite month of the year. And it’s no surprise; the dog days of the summer finally give way to crisp nights and beautifully dry, sunny weather. Here in Yakima, the heart of the world’s largest hop growing area, September is especially golden—actually, a rich, golden green. It’s hop harvest time; a period of anticipation and excitement for those of us intimately involved and deeply passionate about what it takes to craft incredible beers.\r\n\r\nThe six-week harvest ramps up during the waning weeks of August and continues on through September. It’s the culmination of a long year of planning, planting and babying our beloved hops. There’s tons of activity during the harvest with farm operations in full swing for hop take-in and hop quality evaluations. But the highlight of the month for us here at Haas is when the brewers’ begin their annual visits.\r\n\r\nIn years past, Haas has always enjoyed welcoming interested brewers to our farms and facilities each September. As the number of U.S. brewers approaches 4,000, the yearly trek to Yakima has boomed. Many of our customers will be visiting the Haas facilities this year during harvest. It’s a fun, busy and sometimes hectic time of year—but it’s exciting that so many brewers put as much focus on great hops as we do. We do everything we can to make sure they have a great experience while they’re here.\r\n\r\nSpeaking for all of us at Haas—the farm and processing team, the sales team, and the technical and leadership groups—it’s almost impossible to over-emphasize how much we value the personal, trusting relationships forged during the brewers’ visits. Maybe for some, the visit to the hop fields and operations is more of a necessity; part of their job. But, when it comes to the vast majority of brewers I share time with, I get the sense that it’s much more. A welcomed break from the day to day. A chance to learn (and taste!) something new. And, maybe most of all, a festive celebration of the science, art and craft of brewing!','HOP HARVEST. TIME TO TAKE IN THE HOPS…AND PLENTY OF FRIENDS.','','publish','open','open','','hop-harvest-time-to-take-in-the-hopsand-plenty-of-friends','','','2015-09-11 13:40:17','2015-09-11 13:40:17','',0,'http://www.johnihaas.com/?post_type=blog&#038;p=1045',0,'blog','',0),(1046,6,'2015-09-02 16:17:27','2015-09-02 16:17:27','','MMP_294','','inherit','open','open','','mmp_294','','','2015-09-02 16:17:27','2015-09-02 16:17:27','',1045,'http://www.johnihaas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/MMP_294.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1049,1,'2015-09-04 15:49:06','2015-09-04 15:49:06','','Braumeister35@gmail.